data.title: Zucchini sticks for sharing and dipping
data.meta_description: An easy recipe for those zucchini that are growing in your garden
data.text:
ROANOKE, Va. (WDBJ) - Mary Rapoport from the Virginia Egg Council joins us to share a knock-off recipe from one served at a well-known Italian restaurant chain. But this recipe is baked rather than fried, making it a healthier, but still decadent appetizer.

This could also be a fill in for a Sunday night supper for two while watching a game or movie.

Watch how easy this recipe is to make - and enjoy with your friends (or by yourself!)

2 - 7” long zucchini

Salt and pepper

¾ - 1 cup flour

3 eggs, beaten

1½ – 1¾ cups Panko (or breadcrumbs) *

2 tablespoons Italian seasoning (basil, oregano)

Hot pepper flakes (opt.)

Wash zucchini well; slice off each end. Slice squash down the center lengthwise in half, then slice into 8 sticks; then slice in half, widthwise – ending up with 16 sticks per squash. Try to keep sticks uniform. Lay on paper towels and sprinkle liberally with salt. Leave for about 10 minutes so the moisture inside is released. Pat dry. Sticks will be soggy if you omit this step. Sprinkle with pepper.

While zucchini is flushing out the liquid, arrange 3 large cereal bowls in a row with: flour, beaten egg, and Panko with the Italian seasonings blended in. Have a large baking sheet nearby, layered with a piece of parchment. Spray parchment with cooking spray. Preheat oven to 425°F.

Grab a few of the zucchini sticks and dredge in flour, coating all over. Then dip in beaten eggs to coat well. Next, roll in the Panko. Layer on parchment. Continue until all zucchini sticks have been triple coated and arranged on sheet, not touching. Spray with cooking spray and bake for 15 – 20 minutes until very crisp. Sprinkle with hot pepper flakes, if desired.

Plate into a mound and serve with your favorite dipping sauces nearby – tomato sauce/ spicy mayo/ garlic aioli/ gochujang sauce, etc. Enjoy while hot! Makes 32 sticks

*This is a terrific appetizer – meant to be enjoyed hot and shared but filling enough for a light meal for two. They can be reheated in the microwave but will lose some of their crunchiness. Dredging in breadcrumbs rather than Panko will make a less crunchy, but still delicious stick. For those who are gluten intolerant, gluten-free flour and Panko can be used with terrific results.

Zucchini are low in calories, contain fiber, protein, Vitamin C and are versatile! Combined with eggs in this recipe, there’s about 30 grams total protein in this dish.

Virginia Egg Council ~ www.virginiaeggcouncil.org
